# pre-commit Guidance

## Project Context

- Config file: {{ config_file | default(".pre-commit-config.yaml") }}
- Package manager: {{ package_manager | default("detected by Akira") }}

## Configuration

- Keep `.pre-commit-config.yaml` organized by repository, then hook ID, with
  hook-specific `args`, `files`, and `exclude` values close to the hook.
- Pin `rev` to a released tag, never a branch such as `main` or `master`.
- Prefer hook-level `files` filters over broad repo-level excludes when only one
  hook needs special treatment.
- Update hook revisions deliberately with `pre-commit autoupdate` and review
  generated file changes before committing.

## Hook Authoring

- Use `repo: local` for project-specific checks that must run in the project's
  existing environment.
- Use published hooks when isolation and reproducible installation matter; each
  published hook creates its own environment.
- Make local hooks idempotent: running the hook twice should either produce no
  further changes or the same failure.
- Keep entry commands short and route complex behavior through checked-in
  scripts.

## CI Integration

- Run `pre-commit run --all-files` in CI; the default only checks staged files
  and is for developer workstations.
- Cache `PRE_COMMIT_HOME` in CI so isolated hook environments do not rebuild on
  every run.
- Keep CI hook versions and local hook versions from the same config file.
- Treat generated hook edits as a failed check that developers apply locally,
  not as hidden CI mutations.

## Avoid

- `rev: main` or `rev: master`; always use a tag.
- Hooks that modify files without being idempotent.
- Slow hooks such as type checkers or the full test suite as default
  pre-commit hooks.
- Skipping hooks with `--no-verify` as a habit.
